    "crs144": {
        "title": "The Glass Class: Designing Wearable Interfaces",
        "abstract": "The Glass Class: Designing Wearable Interfaces The development of Google Glass and other recent wearable computers has created a significant interest in wearable user interfaces. However there has been little information available on how to create effective wearable experiences. This course will to provide an overview of interface guidelines for wearables and information about the tools available for rapid prototyping and research on a range of different wearable platforms. The course begins with an overview of wearable computing and currently available technology. Key interface design guidelines will be presented using user-centered design principles. Then we introduce a set of tools for quickly prototyping wearable experiences. Finally we will discuss topics for future research and highlight work in these areas. The material will be presented though slides and videos, and attendees will be able to have hands-on experience with Google Glass and other wearable systems. We will also make available prototyping tools, sample source code and key publications. The course will provide attendees with all the material needed to start building wearable applications. The intended audience is interface developers and researchers who are interested in moving into wearable computing. No prior experience is assumed, and many of the tools being shown are suitable for non-programmers. The instructors are Mark Billinghurst from the HIT Lab NZ and Hayes Raffle from Google. Mark is an experienced researcher in Augmented Reality and mobile interfaces who spent a sabbatical as part of the Google Glass team in 2012. Hayes has been working as the Interaction Research Lead for Glass since 2010. ",
        "cAndB": "Attendees will learn to design interfaces for wearable computers like Google Glass through user-centered design principles. They will gain the knowledge to develop prototypes and conduct research on wearable platforms. ",
