    "to111": {
        "title": "Moderated Online Social Therapy: Designing and Evaluating Technology for Mental Health",
        "abstract": "While the use and prevalence of web-based mental health applications has grown over the last decade, many of these services suffer high rates of attrition. This is problematic as face-to-face support for mental health is limited. To determine appropriate design guidelines for increasing engagement we conducted a study of First Episode Psychosis (FEP) patients and reviewed theories on the use of existing online services. We produced a set of design goals, developed an online application that combined social networking and online therapy within a clinician moderated site and conducted a six week trial with a group of young FEP patients. The design goals, based on existing theory including Supportive Accountability and Positive Psychology are operationalised through a model we call MOST (Moderated Online Social Therapy). The trial results indicate that our implementation achieved the design goals and that the MOST model can inform the development of more effective and engaging online therapies. ",
        "cAndB": "We are building an online therapy for psychosis. Early results indicate that a combination of psychotherapy, social interaction and active moderation by clinicians has therapeutic benefits and improves client engagement. ",
