    "to122": {
        "title": "Wild at Home: The Neighborhood as a Living Laboratory for HCI",
        "abstract": "HCI can “turn to the wild” but still stay home. Local community life presents a rich context for under-standing challenges and possibilities of information technology. We summarize and reflect upon a program of participatory design research in which we facilitated activities and experiences of our neighbors through developing a series of community-oriented programs and information systems through the past two dec-ades. We organize these reflections around five overlapping themes: visibility of community actors, crea-tion of community information infrastructures, the role of place-based identity and activity in community, the effectiveness of participatory relationships, and the research designs and methods appropriate. We frame these reflections around a conceptual model of community, and the suggestion that the local com-munity can be a living laboratory for HCI in the wild.",
